ounty's architectural landmarks. And it reveals the intriguing and often surprising links between science, art, and engineering. Laid out in two main sections, the book first introduces the reader to the fundamentals of Milwaukee's geology and its amazing prehuman history, then provides a site-by-site tour guide. Written in an engaging, informal style, this work presents the first in-depth exploration of the interplay among the region's most architecturally significant sites, the materials they're made of, and the sediments and bedrock they're anchored in. Raymond Wiggers crafted Milwaukee in Stone and Clay as an informative and exciting overview of this city. His two decades of experience leading architectural-geology tours have demonstrated the popularity of this approach and the subject matter.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aArchitecturezWisconsinzMilwaukeevGuidebooks. 0aBuilding materialszWisconsinzMilwaukeevGuidebooks. 0aBuilding stoneszWisconsinzMilwaukeevGuidebooks. 0aGeologyzWisconsinzMilwaukeevGuidebooks. 0aStone buildingszWisconsinzMilwaukeevGuidebooks. 4aArchitecture & Preservation. 4aMIDWEST. 7aHISTORY / Historiography.2bisacsh  atour guidebook, Milwaukee, Racine, Kenosha, Wisconsin’s geology, brick, terra cotta, ornamental metals, geology, architectural geology, landmarks.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311075184040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501774669?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501774669423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501774669/original  a978-3-11-075184-0  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles